rows.content:
On the next screen you will see a dot in the middle of the screen. Please click on it with your mouse to see the trial.

You will then see the names of four objects arranged in a quadrant.

Shortly after seeing the names, you will hear a narrative such as "The man thought about the apple."

Please listen to the narrative and click on the object that is being thought about by the character (e.g. the apple) as quickly and accurately as possible.

Your first response is your final answer. This will be underlined in grey when you click in the area containing the word.

You will then see a dot in the middle of the screen which will be coloured green if you selected the correct word, red if you selected the incorrect word, or orange if you did not select any word.

Click on the dot again to see the next trial.

You can take as many breaks as necessary by simply not clicking on the dot between trials.

rows.code:
/* 
Randomisation shuffles rows by group in builder, so we randomly
allocate words to locations given 2 * all possible locations (4*3*2*1 = 24)
in code this could be done by e.g. assigning locations to 4 dictionaries
such as top_left = {x: -225, y: -150}, top_right = {x: 225, y:-150}, ...
shuffling the set pseudocode: randomised = shuffle(c(top_left, top_right, ...))
getting all static word info in var = items, and assigning locations based on the shuffled order, e.g. 
items["x_1"] = randomised[1][1], 
items["x_1"] = randomised[1][2]
Then push this final table to this.options.templateParameters to overwrite the loop content.

However, this method always randomly draws from the 4 possible locations objects can be in, and doesn't balance target placement like in the builder.
*/
